    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Motions Snag Cable TV Trials</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: A flurry of legal motions threatens to delay the trials of two men from Queens charged with crimes related to cable-television franchising.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: A flurry of legal motions threatens to delay the trials of two men from Queens charged with crimes related to cable-television franchising.</p>
        <p>A flurry of legal motions threatens to delay the trials of two men from Queens charged with crimes related to cable-television franchising.</p>
        <p>In one trial, scheduled to begin June 8 in State Supreme Court in Queens, the state's administrative judge in Queens, Francis X. Smith, will face charges of perjury and criminal contempt over grand-jury testimony. In the second trial, to begin in the same court after the Smith trial, John A. Zaccaro, a real-estate broker and husband of former Representative Geraldine A. Ferraro, is charged with trying to extort a bribe for a Queens franchise.</p>
        <p>Lawyers for Justice Smith have asked Acting Justice John S. Thorp Jr. to remove Paul W. Pickelle as chief prosecutor, because the defense planned to call him as a witness.</p>
        <p>Mr. Zaccaro's lawyers have asked the Appellate Division to throw out the counts of bribe-seeking and first-degree attempted extortion on a jurisdictional ground, because Mr. Zaccaro is charged with having asked for the payoff at a meeting in Manhattan.</p>
        <p>Justice Thorp has ruled the counts can be prosecuted in Queens, although he dismissed a count of second-degree attempted extortion, for which he said there was no venue in Queens. The District Attorney's office has filed papers saying it will ask the Appellate Division to reinstate the count.</p>
        <p>Justice Smith, who has been suspended, and Mr. Zaccaro have denied any wrongdoing.</p>
      </block>
